# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On 15 February 2003, a coordinated day of protests was held across the world in which people in more than 600 cities expressed opposition to the imminent Iraq War.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was part of a series of protests and political events that had begun in 2002 and continued as the invasion, war, and occupation took place.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The day was described by social movement researchers as "the largest protest event in human history".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to BBC News, between six and ten million people took part in protests in up to sixty countries over the weekend of 15 and 16 February.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in Europe.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The one in Rome involved around three million people, and is listed in the 2004 *Guinness Book of World Records* as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Madrid hosted the second largest rally with more than 1.5 million people protesting against the invasion of Iraq.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, three smaller protests were held the following day, attended by foreigners and domestic students.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2002, the United States government began to argue for the necessity of invading Iraq.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This formally began with a speech by US President George W.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bush to the United Nations General Assembly on 12 September 2002 which argued that the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein was violating United Nations (UN) resolutions, primarily on weapons of mass destruction, and that this necessitated action.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposed war was controversial with many people questioning the motives of the US government and its rationale.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One poll which covered 41 countries claimed that less than 10% would support an invasion of Iraq without UN sanction and that half would not support an invasion under any circumstances.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war groups worldwide organised public protests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the French academic Dominique Reynié, between 3 January and 12 April 2003, 36 million people across the globe took part in almost 3,000 anti‑war protests, the demonstrations on 15 February 2003 being the largest and most prolific.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The 15 February international protests were unprecedented not only in terms of the size of the demonstrations but also in terms of the international coordination involved.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Immanuel Wallerstein has spoken of the international protests as being organised by the forces of "the camps of Porto Alegre and Davos" in reference to the emergence of global social movements who had been organising around international events such as the 2001 World Social Forum in Porto Alegre.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The idea for an international day of demonstrations was first raised by the British anti-capitalist group Globalise Resistance (GR) in the wake of an anti-war demonstration in Britain of 400,000 on 28 September.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time GR was involved in planning for the Florence European Social Forum (ESF) and brought up the suggestion at an ESF planning meeting.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to GR's Chris Nineham, "There was considerable controversy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Some delegates were worried it would alienate the mainstream of the movement.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposal was accepted and at the final rally of the ESF, in November 2002, the call officially went out for Europe-wide demonstrations on 15 February 2003.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This call was firmed up in December at a planning meeting for the following ESF which took place in Copenhagen in 2003.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This meeting was attended by delegates from many European anti-war organisations, the US group United for Peace and Justice, and representatives of groups from the Philippines.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The decision was taken to set up a Europe-wide anti-war website and to commit to spreading organisational coordination both within and beyond Europe.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An email network connecting the different national organisations across Europe, and eventually also the different US groups, was set up.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In December 2002, the Cairo Anti-war Conference pledged to organize demonstrations in Egypt and the International Campaign Against Aggression on Iraq (which came out of the Cairo conference) sought to co-ordinate more demonstrations across the world.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around this time, the US anti-war group International ANSWER called for actions in North America supporting the proposed protests in Europe.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another important platform for the spreading call to demonstrate internationally occurred at the World Social Forum in Porto Alegre, Brazil which took place at the end of 2002.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] European delegates sought to popularize the plan for the increasingly international demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They met with some success, including the organisation of an anti‑war assembly which was attended by almost 1,000 people.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The song "Boom!", by System of a Down, had a music video filmed on the day of the protest, showing the many protest locations and people's opinions on the Iraq War.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations took place across Europe and some of the largest drawing attendance figures in the tens of thousands in many cities.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately one-fifth of the total demonstrators worldwide protested in Europe.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austria, 30,000 people (SW estimate) took to the streets of its capital, Vienna.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Switzerland in order to "concentrate the movement" most activists agreed to organise a single demonstration for the whole country in Bern.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day roughly 40,000 people joined the protest in front of the Bundeshaus, the seat of the Swiss federal government and parliament.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration, which ran under the slogan **Nein zum Krieg gegen Irak – Kein Blut für Öl!** (No to war in Iraq – no blood for oil!) was the largest in Switzerland since 1945.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Slovenia, roughly 3,000 people gathered in Ljubljana's central park of Congress Square, supported by the mayor Danica Simšič, and marched the streets in one of the largest demonstrations since independence in 1991.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Benelux countries had large demonstrations for their total population size.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Belgium organisers had expected around 30,000 people to attend a demonstration in Brussels, which is the home of the European Parliament.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They were shocked by a turn out of approximately 100,000 people (WSWS and GLW estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march took over 3 hours to cross the city.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Netherlands saw around 70,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 75,000 people (WSWS estimate) protest in Amsterdam.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was the country's largest demonstration since the anti-nuclear campaigns of the 1980s.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti war website antiwar.com reports that 8,000-14,000 people were present at protests in Luxembourg, however they do not provide a citation for this figure.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bosnia and Herzegovina saw around 100 protesters gather in Mostar.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This protest spanned the sectarian divide with both Bosniaks and Croats attending.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in Croatia where 10,000 people (WSWS estimate) took part in a protest in the capital city of Zagreb.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Croatia also saw protests in Osijek, Vukovar, Knin, Zadar, Šibenik, Split and Dubrovnik.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Cyprus saw a demonstration of between 500 (*USA Today* estimate) and more than 800 people (SW estimate) at the British army base in Dhekelia.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Enduring heavy rain protesters briefly blocked the base.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They then marched to Pyla village where they watched other demonstrations occurring across the world on a giant screen.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was mostly attended by Greek Cypriots but they were joined by some Turkish Cypriots.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the Czech Republic, over 1,000 people joined a rally at Jan Palach Square in Prague.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Czech philosopher Erazim Kohak addressed the crowd, saying, "War is not a solution, war is a problem." Protesters listened to music and speeches before marching to the Czech government building, where they submitted petitions, then march continued to the US embassy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In France, there were demonstrations in somewhere between twenty (*Observer* estimate) and eighty cities (WSWS estimate); the organisers estimated that over half a million marched in total.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration took place in Paris, where around 100,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 200,000 (WSWS estimate) people marched through the streets, ending in a rally at the Place de la Bastille.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This location's role in the French Revolution was considered to give it a historical significance.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Toulouse of around 10,000 people.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Germany, coaches brought people from over 300 German towns to Berlin to join a demonstration of 300,000 (police estimate) to 500,000 (organizers' estimate) people; the largest demonstration that had occurred in Berlin for several decades.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters, including members of Gerhard Schröder's government, filled the boulevard between the Brandenburg Gate and the Victory Column.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Athens, Greece, 150,000 people (WSWS estimate) demonstrated.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was generally peaceful, but a small group clashed with police.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police fired tear gas at the group some of whom threw rocks and petrol bombs.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police reported that the trouble was down to a group of anarchists who had split off from the main demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Ireland, the Dublin march was only expected to draw 20,000 people, but the actual figure was given variously as 80,000 (police estimate), 90,000 (BBC estimate), 100,000 (*Guardian* estimate) or 150,000 (Socialist Worker (SW) estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march went from Parnell Square, passing the Department of Foreign Affairs at St.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Stephen's Green, and on to the Dame Street for a rally where popular Irish folk singer Christy Moore, Kíla and Labour Party politician Michael D.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Higgins were among many speakers from the platform.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march disrupted traffic for more than four hours.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters demanded that the Irish government stop allowing the United States military to use Ireland's Shannon Airport as a transatlantic stop-off point in bringing soldiers to the Middle East.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the global day of protest took place in Italy in Rome.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Nearly 3,000 buses and thirty trains were specially chartered to bring people to the demonstration, which was organised under the slogan "Stop the war; no ifs or buts".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The organisers were shocked at the size of the turn out and the unexpected number of people forced the demonstration to set off two hours early.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The size of the demonstration meant that the majority of demonstrators did not make it into the final rally and in total three million people (organisers' estimate, supported by the Guinness Book of World Records) were on the streets.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was listed in the 2004 Guinness Book of World Records as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the *Green Left Weekly* (GLW), the demonstration contained people from across Italian society; "Catholic nuns and priests marched alongside young people with dreadlocks, nose rings and Palestinian scarves.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Christians, anarchists and communists mingled".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately 1,000 demonstrated (SW estimate) in Malta.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] After the demonstration an anti-war concert was held in the capital, Valletta.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Norway saw its biggest series of protests since 1917.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in its capital Oslo were more than 60,000 protesters (Police estimate and Socialist Worker estimate) joining a demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of around 15,000 took place in Bergen and Trondheim, and 10,000 in Stavanger.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests also took place in at least 30 towns across the country.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the rally in Oslo the vice-chair of the Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions (LO) spoke from the platform claiming that "Bush only cares about American oil interests".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Denmark 20,000 to 30,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) took part in a march in the capital city, Copenhagen.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Sweden, 35,000 demonstrated in Stockholm. and about 25,000 in Gothenburg.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Helsinki, Finland, an estimated 15,000 people participated in one of the largest mass-protests in the republic's history.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was a demonstration in Warsaw, Poland of 10,000 people (SW estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration through central Warsaw passed the US embassy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another protest, organized by the local Wrocław Anti-War Coalition (WKA), was held in the city of Wrocław in the market square by the town hall, with 400–500 people participating.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lisbon, police estimated that around 35,000 people gathered to march through the city.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Three former Portuguese prime ministers were in attendance.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Russia, which had several demonstrations, the largest occurred in Moscow, with 200,000 people (WSWS estimate) in attendance.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small demonstrations also took place in Serbia, where there was a demonstration of 200 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Belgrade.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was estimated that 1,000 people marched in the capital of Slovakia, Bratislava.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Barcelona also had a large, with estimates of 350,000 (Delegación de Gobierno), 1,300,000 (Barcelona city hall and Police) or 1,500,000 (GLW) people joining a demonstration which moved from the Passeig de Gràcia to the Plaça de Tetuan.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The city of Oviedo had a population of 180,000 and a turnout of 100,000.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The main demonstration in Turkey took place in Istanbul, thousands (SW estimate) demonstrated.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The local authorities had banned the protest claiming to have worries about national security, however the protest organisers went ahead with the rally under the cover of calling a press conference.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations in Adana, Ankara, İzmir, Zonguldak, İzmit, Antalya and Muğla.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Ukraine of around 2,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a "Rock against the war" rally in Kyiv's central square.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the lead-up to 15 February, the Stop the War Coalition was organising the march from a small office donated by the National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They planned for the two marches to merge at Piccadilly Circus and then proceed to a rally at Hyde Park.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The negotiations for this plan faltered when the Labour government's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport Tessa Jowell initially instructed the Royal Parks agency to deny permission for the rally in Hyde Park for safety reasons and to protect the grass.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Trafalgar Square was suggested by Jowell as the alternative venue, but the Mayor of London Ken Livingstone insisted it was of insufficient size.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The government's decision was reversed by 5 February.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sections of the media supported this demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The *Daily Mirror* gave large coverage in the lead up to the march and provided thousands of placards on the day.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration also received sponsorship support from Greenpeace and Mecca-Cola.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As the date for the march approached the BBC was predicting that around 500,000 people would attend, while StWC was hoping for numbers to top the symbolically significant million mark.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The British Stop the War Coalition (Stop) claimed the protest in London was the largest political demonstration in the city's history.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police estimated attendance as well in excess of 750,000 people and the BBC estimated that around a million attended.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The weather, on the day of the protest was grey and cold, but reports noted that people remained "in high spirits" as London became gridlocked and protesters were stuck for hours at Gower Street and the Embankment, the two starting points for the march.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police began the march earlier than intended on safety grounds because of the number of people who had arrived in central London.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Hundreds of coaches brought protesters from 250 towns and cities across the UK, with around 100 coaches coming from Wales alone.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many commentators noted the diversity of those attending the march.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] All police leave in the capital was cancelled for the event, though Scotland Yard later said that it passed off almost without incident.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters who managed to reach Hyde Park in time heard various speakers, including Harold Pinter, George Galloway, Tony Benn and Bianca Jagger however many were not able to reach the rally as those travelling home by coach had to leave before completing the march route.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters at the back end of the march did not reach Hyde Park until hours after the speakers and performers had finished.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Charles Kennedy, then the leader of the Liberal Democrats, was a late addition to the list of speakers.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some media speculation that he only decided to speak after a lead article in *The Guardian* was critical of his absence from the planned speaker list.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Because of the size of the march, accurate estimates of the number of people in attendance are difficult.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It is relatively uncontentious that the march was the largest ever political demonstration in the UK and the biggest taking to the streets since the Golden Jubilee weekend in 2002.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In an ICM poll for *The Guardian* (14 February 2003 – 16 February 2003), 6% of people claimed that someone from their household went on the march or had intended to.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Stop claims that this translates into 1.25 million households and thus supports the estimate of two million people, assuming that more than one person could come from each household.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] RadioVague in conjunction with the now defunct CableRadio broadcast speeches, music and interviews from the event to the internet throughout the day using a satellite uplink provided by Psand.net.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A sole person demonstrated in opposition to the march outside the Iraqi section of the Jordanian Embassy on the day – Jacques More a writer from Croydon – with a placard saying that, although a last resort, war is necessary "[w]hen evil dictators rule and murder their own people".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Ten years on writer Ian Sinclair assembled an oral history of the demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Journalist Ellie Mae O'Hagan, a UK Uncut activist, told Sinclair that despite its size "it did absolutely nothing".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other witnesses, such as Milan Rai, are of the opposite opinion: "We achieved a lot, and a hell of a lot more than we realise".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tariq Ali, one of the speakers in February 2003, said at the tenth anniversary: "I didn't quite tell them 'Blair is going to go to war regardless of today' but I knew that".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "It was a huge show of anger but that's about it.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "One demonstration never overturned government policy overnight – or very rarely – and on something as strategic and massive as that", commented Seumas Milne in an interview with *The Quietus* online magazine in October 2012.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In addition to the demonstrations in England, the United Kingdom also saw protests in Scotland.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war activists planned a demonstration in Glasgow which ended at the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre (SECC) where the Labour Party was holding a conference for party members.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party requested that the SECC refuse permission for a stage and PA system outside the conference hall.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In response to this the then Scottish Socialist Party MSP Tommy Sheridan tabled a motion in the Scottish Parliament to allow the event to take place, condemning what he claimed were attempts to "stifle all opposition to warmonger Blair".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party was unsuccessful in blocking the demonstrators' plans.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tony Blair was due to give a speech at the same time as the protesters would have arrived outside the conference centre, but the speech was rescheduled to an earlier time to avoid this.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day around 50,000 people according to the *Guardian* joined the march, which started at Glasgow Green.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the time the front of the march had travelled the 2 miles (3.2 km) to the SECC, Blair had delivered his speech and had left the area.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Northern Irish march was held in Belfast, where 10,000 (*Guardian* estimate) to 20,000 (SW estimate) protesters from across the sectarian divide joined the demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march started at the Arts College at 14:30 and moved through that Royal Avenue towards Belfast City Hall.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Prominent politicians from Sinn Féin, the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and the centrist Alliance Party joined the protest.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sinn Féin president Gerry Adams spoke from the platform at the end rally saying "If President Bush and Mr Blair want war, it should be war against poverty and for equality." There was also a rally in Newry in County Down attending by hundreds of protesters (BBC estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Canada saw protests in 70 cities and towns (WSWS estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in Montreal where more than 100,000 people protested (SW and WSWS each estimated 150,000) despite windchill temperatures below −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 80,000 people joined a demonstration in Toronto, 40,000 in Vancouver, 18,000 (by police estimates) in Edmonton, 8,000 in Victoria, 4,000 in Halifax and 6,000 in Ottawa.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were protests in 70 cities in total.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] These demonstrations took place despite very cold weather, average temperatures were below −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Chicoutimi, 1,500 protested in windchill temperatures of −40 °C (−40 °F) wind-chill temperature in what was one of the coldest marches on that global day of protest.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place all across the United States of America with CBS reporting that 150 U.S. cities had protests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the World Socialist Web Site, protests took place in 225 different communities.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in the nation's largest cities including Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York City, but there were also smaller rallies in towns such as Gainesville, Georgia; Macomb, Illinois; and Juneau, Alaska, among scores of others.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Organisers of the New York City protest had hoped to march past the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a week before the march, police claimed that they would not be able to ensure order and District Court Judge Barbara Jones ruled against allowing the route.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Instead, protesters were only permitted to hold a stationary rally.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On that day, over 300 buses and four special trains brought protesters in from across the country.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] BBC estimates that 100,000 protesters took part in a rally near the UN headquarters.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among those taking part was the 9/11 Families For Peaceful Tomorrows, a group made up of some relatives of victims of the attacks on the World Trade Center.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Speakers included politicians, church leaders and entertainers, such as actress Susan Sarandon and South African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As people tried to reach the rally area they ended up constituting an unplanned march, stretching twenty blocks down First Avenue and overflowing onto Second and Third Avenue.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In total estimates range from 300,000 to 400,000 protesters (WSWS estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests were largely peaceful though a small group of protesters who were reported to have broken off from the main rally, caused damage to property in Union Square, and threw stones at police officers, which resulted in forty arrests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were numerous complaints that the New York City Police Department (NYPD) were too heavy-handed.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many streets were blocked off and protesters reported feeling hemmed in and scared.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the end of the day, police reported that there had been roughly 275 arrests; organisers dispute this number, claiming that there were 348 arrests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, NYPD spokesman Michael O'Looney denied the charges claiming that the tape was "filled with special effects" and that it did not prove the police had not been provoked.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At a demonstration in Los Angeles, California, 50,000 (WSWS estimate) to 60,000 (GLW estimate) protesters (CNN said "thousands") marched down Hollywood Boulevard filling it for four blocks.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Amongst the protesters were the actors Martin Sheen and Mike Farrell and director Rob Reiner.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Martin Sheen, who at the time was playing a fictitious U.S. president in *The West Wing*, said that "None of us can stop this war ... there is only one guy that can do that and he lives in the White House".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other activists in California originally planned to hold a protest in San Francisco on the Saturday but they changed to the Sunday in order not to conflict with the city's Chinese New Year's parade.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was held on Sunday 16 February.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The BBC estimated the crowd size to be 150,000 people, while protest organisers and police agreed that the crowd count was 200,000 people.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a *San Francisco Chronicle* photographic investigation estimated that the number in attendance at the peak period was closer to 65,000 people, although it did not state how many people were in attendance for the duration of the demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some controversy over Rabbi Michael Lerner not being selected as a speaker for the rally at the end of the demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Lerner claimed that he was not picked to speak for reasons of antisemitism due to his support for the existence of the Israeli state.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austin, Texas, 10,000 protestors marched down Congress Avenue from the state capitol building.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Colorado Springs, 4,000 protesters were dispersed with pepper spray, tear gas, stun guns and batons.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 34 were arrested on failure to disperse and other charges and at least two protesters had to have hospital treatment.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Seattle, organisers aimed to have 20 to 30 thousand people join a march from Seattle Center following a giant blue planet, the emblem adopted by the march organisers.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day 50,000 people (GLW estimate) turned out to protest under the dual slogan "Stop the war on Iraq; Stop the war on immigrants", more than on the Seattle protests against the WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations also took place in Philadelphia, where thousands (CNN estimate) joined a march to the Liberty Bell, and in Chicago, where 10,000 people demonstrated (GLW estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Florida a small number of protesters staged a naked protest on Palm Beach.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They initially had some problems getting permission for the action, but on the Thursday before, a U.S.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] District court ruled that the planned nude protest was legal at the public beach.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Most of the attendees had come from the four-day Mid-Winter Naturist Festival that was taking place at the same time.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration of 900 people (*USA Today* estimate) on the island of Puerto Rico.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The chief demonstration in Mexico took place in Mexico City where around 10,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a demonstration which ended with a rally at a heavily guarded US embassy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among the demonstrators was Nobel Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchú.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place across South America including Uruguay, where their protest took place on 14 February.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An estimated 70,000 people marched down Montevideo's Avenida 18.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Brazil, a protest led by President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva was attended by 1,500 marchers (Police estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Buenos Aires, Argentina, an estimate of 50,000 protesters attended which included some veterans of the Falklands War of 1982.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Areas in Asia with large Muslim populations, in particular the countries of the West Asia, had the highest levels of opposition to the proposed Iraq war, however demonstrations in many of these countries were relatively small.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The reasons for this are complex, but one factor that is commonly cited is the suppression of protest movements by the conservative leaders of those countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Iraq, the country in which the war would take place, protesters marched down Palestine Street in Baghdad where several thousand Iraqis—many carrying Kalashnikov rifles—joined in the global protests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Unlike the vast majority of protests across the world the protest in Baghdad was also in support of the Baathist regime; it was called by Saddam Hussein as "World Anger Day".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters carried posters of Saddam and burned US flags.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A large protest also took place on the streets of Damascus in Syria, which borders Iraq.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters chanted anti-U.S. and anti-Israeli slogans while marching to the "People's Assembly" in a demonstration of between 10,000 (GLW estimate) to 200,000 protesters (CBS estimate and *USA Today* estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lebanon, 10,000 protesters (CBS, GLW estimate) took part in a demonstration in Beirut.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protest ended early when it rained heavily.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations of 5,000 people (GLW estimate) in Amman, Jordan.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Israel there was a demonstration in Tel Aviv of approximately 2,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 3,000 people (GLW and WSWS estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration contained both Arabs and Jews.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was organized by a wide range of organizations including the Communist Party of Israel, the National Democratic Assembly, the Arab Democratic Party, the Independent Media Center, the Alternative Information Center, Ta'ayush, the Gush Shalom movement, and the Organization for Democratic Action.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, it was boycotted by other left-wing groups, including Peace Now and Meretz.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was coordinated with a similar demonstration which took place in Ramallah.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests took place across Japan mostly being held outside US military bases.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the day took place in Shibuya, where 5,000 (SW estimate) people marched.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, there was a demonstration of 25,000 in Tokyo on Friday, the day before as well as smaller demonstrations in Osaka and other cities.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Tokyo protests contained Japanese veterans of World War II and survivors of the 1945 atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 3,000 people (SW estimate) joined an illegal demonstration in the Malaysian city of Kuala Lumpur despite police warnings that any participants in a protest would face stern action.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration ended at the US embassy at Jalan Tun Razak.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Taiwan had a protest of more than 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Taipei under the slogan of "No Blood for Oil".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] India saw protests across the country including 10,000 (BBC estimate) in Calcutta.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Bangladesh 2,000 people joined a demonstration in Dhaka.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In South Korea, there was a demonstration of 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) which took place in the capital city Seoul.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest started with a rally at Marronnier Park after which there was a demonstration that ended in Jongmyo were the size of the protest increased in size to 3,000 people (WSWS estimate).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Jongmyo was surrounded by riot police who almost out numbered the protesters.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests also took place in the South Korean cities of Busan, Daegu, Daejeon, Gwangju and Wonju.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, China, three protests were held the following day, attended by about 450 people in total, including foreigners and domestic students.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Johannesburg, around 8,000-10,000 people joined in a colorful and peaceful protest.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They toyi-toyied and marched, stopping at the U.S.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Consulate General where riot police formed a protective chain around the entrance.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Cape Town 5,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 20,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) joined a demonstration march which started at 10 in the morning on Keizersgracht road and ended at the offices of the US consulate-general which was guarded by a ring of riot police, where there was a rally with speakers.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests were organised by the Anti-War Coalition and the Stop the War campaign of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of thousands of people also took place at Durban and Bloemfontein.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A number of prominent ANC politicians attended marches.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the Cape Town rally the South African Minister, Pallo Jordan addressed the protesters saying; "We will stop the war.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A protest of around 3,000 (SW estimate) in the Tunisian city of Sfax was attacked by police who beat the protesters with batons and truncheons, injuring at least 20.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests in Fiji took place on the day before, on Friday morning, heralding the weekend of demonstrations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters handed floral Valentine's Day messages to the representatives of the US, British and Australian governments urging them to avoid the war.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Friday also saw protests in Melbourne, where around 150,000 people (BBC estimate) joined a demonstration.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the Saturday protests also took place in Australia's national capital (Canberra), with 20,000 protesters.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Sydney demonstration on Sunday 16 February included a feeder march of 10,000 trade unionists, with 200,000 (BBC estimate) to 250,000 (Sydney Morning Herald estimate) demonstrating in Sydney.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Across the six state capitals an estimated 600,000 demonstrated in cities around the country.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Beyond the capitals, many major cities and towns around Australia had protests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At protests in Australia in Bellingen, New South Wales around 2,500 people (SW estimate) joined a rally at the towns sports ground.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As well as hearing from speakers, the demonstrators were entertained by a group of a cappella singers called 'The Bushbombs'.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The rally was about as large as the town's population.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The first actual demonstration of the day took place in New Zealand where 10,000 people demonstrated in Auckland and Wellington.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Auckland march was bigger than expected, forcing police to shut off Queen Street.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] People were reported to be still starting the march as those at the front of the march reached a rally in Myers Park several kilometres away.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Wellington the march had to carry on after the then planned end point as there were too many people to fit into the park.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 400 to 500 people marched in Hamilton.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in at least 18 other centres, including Dunedin, Thames, Opotiki, Whakatane, Whangarei, Timaru and Rotorua, and Picnic for Peace in Christchurch.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A group of scientists at the US McMurdo Station held a rally on the ice at the edge of the Ross Sea.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time, many commentators were hopeful that this global mobilization of unprecedented scale would stop the coming Iraq war.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] *The New York Times* writer Patrick Tyler claimed that they showed that there were "two superpowers on the planet – the United States, and worldwide public opinion".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The unprecedented size of the demonstrations was widely taken to indicate that the majority of people across the world opposed the war.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the potential effect of the protests was generally dismissed by pro-war politicians.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Her view was borne out as the day of protests, along with the protests that followed it, failed to stop the war.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protests and other public opposition were seen as a key factor in the decisions of the governments of many countries, such as Canada, to not send troops to Iraq, and of Turkey to deny coalition use of airbases in its territory.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests have also been cited as a factor strengthening the hand of the "uncommitted six" members of the United Nations Security Council - Angola, Cameroon, Chile, Mexico, and Pakistan.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Though demonstrations against the Iraq war and subsequent occupation continued, none of the demonstrations through to 2011 matched the 15 February protest in terms of size.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One suggested explanation for this is that people became disillusioned with marching as a political tactic because of the failure of these demonstrations to achieve their explicit aim.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2006, three years after the protest day, in an article arguing for people to attend a further march, Mike Marqusee put forward two counter arguments to this.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Firstly, he claimed that it was too soon to judge the long-term significance of the demonstrations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As examples, he stated, "People who took part in the non-cooperation campaigns in India in the 20s and 30s had to wait a long time for independence," and "There were eight years of protest and more than 2 million dead before the Vietnam war came to an end".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Secondly, he claimed that while the effect of marching may be uncertain, the effect of not marching would make it more likely that the occupation would continue.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Despite failing in its explicit aim, the 15 February global day of anti-war protests had many effects that, according to some, were not directly intended.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to United Kingdom left-wing anti-war activist Salma Yaqoob, one of these was that they were a powerful antidote to the idea that the war was a "Clash of Civilizations", or a religious war, an idea she claimed was propagated both by Western leaders and reactionary forces in the Arab world.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This is echoed in the words of former Hizb ut-Tahrir organiser Hadiya Masieh who said of the non-Muslims marching in London "How could we demonise people who obviously opposed aggression against Muslims?".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/1998-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **1998 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place in November 1998 in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/1998-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference included the 4th Conference of the Parties (COP4) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/1998-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It had been expected that the remaining issues unresolved in Kyoto would be finalized at this meeting.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/1998-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, the complexity and difficulty of finding agreement on these issues proved insurmountable, and instead the parties adopted a 2-year "Plan of Action" to advance efforts and to devise mechanisms for implementing the Kyoto Protocol, to be completed by 2000.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/1998-united-nations-climate-change-conference] During the conference, Argentina and Kazakhstan expressed their commitment to take on the greenhouse gas emissions reduction obligation, the first two non-Annex countries to do so.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2001 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place from October 29 to November 10, 2001, in Marrakesh, Morocco.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference included the 7th Conference of the Parties (COP7) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The negotiators wrapped up the work on the Buenos Aires Plan of Action, finalizing most of the operational details and setting the stage for nations to ratify the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The completed package of decisions is known as the Marrakesh Accords.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United States delegation maintained its observer role, declining to participate actively in the negotiations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The date of the World Summit on Sustainable Development (August–September 2002) was put forward as a target to bring the Kyoto Protocol into force.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2001-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The World Summit on Sustainable Development (WSSD) was to be held in Johannesburg, South Africa.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2002 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place from 23 October – 1 November 2002, in New Delhi, India.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference included the 8th Conference of the Parties (COP8) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference adopted the Delhi Ministerial Declaration that, amongst others, called for efforts by developed countries to transfer technology and minimize the impact of climate change on developing countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It is also approved the New Delhi work programme on Article 6 of the Convention.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The COP8 was marked by Russia's hesitation, stating that it needed more time to think it over.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Kyoto Protocol could enter into force once it was ratified by 55 countries, including countries responsible for 55 per cent of the developed world's 1990 carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2002-united-nations-climate-change-conference] With the United States (36.1% share of developed-world carbon dioxide) and Australia refusing ratification, Russia's agreement (17% of global emissions in 1990) was required to meet the ratification criteria and therefore Russia could delay the process.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2003-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2003 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place between 1–12 December 2003 in Milan, Italy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2003-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference included the 9th Conference of the Parties (COP9) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2003-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The parties agreed to use the Adaptation Fund established at COP7 in 2001 primarily in supporting developing countries better adapt to climate change.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2003-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fund would also be used for capacity-building through technology transfer.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2003-united-nations-climate-change-conference] At the conference, the parties also agreed to review the first national reports submitted by 110 non-Annex I countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2004-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2004 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place between December 6 and December 17, 2004, in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2004-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference included the 10th Conference of the Parties (COP10) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2004-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The parties discussed the progress made since the first United Nations Climate Change Conference ten years ago and its future challenges, with special emphasis on climate change mitigation and adaptation.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2004-united-nations-climate-change-conference] To promote developing countries better adapt to climate change, the Buenos Aires Plan of Action was adopted.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2004-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The parties also began discussing the post-Kyoto mechanism, on how to allocate emission reduction obligation following 2012, when the first commitment period ends.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2005 United Nations Climate Change Conference** took place between November 28 and December 9, 2005, in Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference included the 11th Conference of the Parties (COP11) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC), and was the first *Meeting of the Parties* (MOP1) to the Kyoto Protocol since their initial meeting in Kyoto in 1997.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference was one of the largest intergovernmental conferences on climate change ever.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The event marked the entry into force of the Kyoto Protocol on 16 February 2005.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Hosting more than 10,000 delegates, it was one of Canada's largest international events ever and the largest gathering in Montreal since Expo 67.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Montreal Action Plan was an agreement to "extend the life of the Kyoto Protocol beyond its 2012 expiration date and negotiate deeper cuts in greenhouse gas emissions" by starting negotiations, without delay on an extension of the protocol.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2005-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Canada's environment minister, at the time, Stéphane Dion, said the agreement provides a "map for the future".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference**, more commonly referred to as **COP26**, was the 26th United Nations Climate Change conference, held at the SEC Centre in Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom, from 31 October to 13 November 2021.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The president of the conference was UK cabinet minister Alok Sharma.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The result of COP26 was the Glasgow Climate Pact, negotiated through consensus of the representatives of the 197 attending parties.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Owing to late interventions from India and China that weakened a move to end coal power and fossil fuel subsidies, the conference ended with the adoption of a less stringent resolution than some anticipated.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nevertheless, the pact was the first climate deal to explicitly commit to reducing the use of coal.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It included wording that encouraged more urgent greenhouse gas emissions cuts and promised more climate finance for developing countries to adapt to climate impacts.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the midst of the conference, on 6 November 2021, a march against inadequate action at the conference, as well as for other climate change-related issues, became the largest protest in Glasgow since anti-Iraq War marches in 2003.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Additional rallies took place in 100 other countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United Kingdom holds the presidency of COP26 until the start of COP27.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Initially, the Minister of State for Energy and Clean Growth, Claire Perry, was appointed as president of the conference, but she was removed on 31 January 2020, several months after she had stepped down as an MP.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Former Prime Minister David Cameron and former Foreign Secretary William Hague declined to take the role.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 February 2020, Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Secretary Alok Sharma was appointed.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 8 January 2021, Sharma was succeeded by Kwasi Kwarteng as Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Secretary and moved to the Cabinet Office, in order to focus on the presidency full-time.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nigel Topping, the former CEO of climate change action organization We Mean Business, was appointed the UK Government's High Level Climate Action Champion for COP26.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Italy partnered with the UK in leading COP26.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] For the most part, their role was in preparatory work such as the hosting of a pre-COP session and an event for young people called Youth4Climate 2020: Driving Ambition.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] These events took place between 28 September and 2 October 2020 in Milan.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic, in April 2020 the conference was postponed to 31 October – 12 November 2021.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Both host countries, Italy and the UK, were heavily affected by the pandemic, and the venue of the conference, the SEC Centre in Glasgow, was converted in May 2020 into a temporary hospital for COVID-19 patients in Scotland.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Earlier in 2021, the UK and Italy hosted summits of the G7 and G20, respectively.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Independent observers noted that though not directly related, the postponement gave the international community time to respond to the outcome of the United States presidential election, held in November 2020.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] President Donald Trump had withdrawn the United States from the Paris Agreement, although this could not take effect until the day after the election; while his Democratic challengers pledged to immediately rejoin and increase ambition to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Joe Biden did so upon being elected as president.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] At the conference, Biden apologized for Trump's withdrawal from the agreement.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previous summits have been sponsored by fossil fuel companies.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] To reduce this influence, the UK government decided that sponsors "have to have real commitments in place to help them reach net zero in the near future".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The first principal partners included three British energy companies and a banking and insurance company.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Before the summit councils in and around Glasgow pledged to plant 18 million trees during the following decade: the Clyde Climate Forest (CCF) is projected to increase tree coverage in the urban areas of the Greater Glasgow region to 20%.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In September 2021, the conference was urged by Climate Action Network to ensure attendees would be able to attend in spite of travel restrictions related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the months before the conference, the British government had restrictions on travel from certain countries in place, and COVID passports were required in certain venues.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Critics suggested unequal deployment of COVID-19 vaccines worldwide could exclude the participation of representatives of poorer countries most affected by climate change.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UK subsequently relaxed travel rules for delegations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Only four Pacific Islands nations sent delegations due to COVID-19 travel restrictions, with most island nations compelled to send smaller teams than they otherwise would have.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Organizers have in place numerous COVID-19 rules for attendees, dependent on vaccination status.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 4 June 2021, a nighttime light projection onto the Tolbooth Steeple was installed, under the Climate Clock initiative.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The projected Deadline and Lifeline statistics count the time window before 1.5 °C warming would become inevitable, and the percentage of global energy delivered through renewables, respectively.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Scottish Events Campus (SEC), known as the Blue Zone, temporarily became United Nations territory: the other main venue is the Green Zone at Glasgow Science Centre.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The summit was described as receiving "the cleanest electricity in the UK", as 70% was supplied from low-carbon nuclear power from plants in Torness and Hunterston B, while the rest mostly came from wind power.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The provision of medical services for the event was provided by BASICS Scotland, Amvale Medical and the Scottish Ambulance Service.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The medical centre was visited by both Scottish National Clinical Director Jason Leitch and Scottish Health Secretary Humza Yousaf during the conference.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Twenty-five thousand delegates from nearly 200 countries were expected to attend, and around 120 heads of state came.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Australian prime minister Scott Morrison spoke.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Czech prime minister Andrej Babiš denounced the proposed European Union Fit for 55 laws, part of the European Green Deal, saying that the bloc "can achieve nothing without the participation of the largest polluters such as China or the USA".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Prince Charles addressed the opening ceremony in person.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Queen Elizabeth, having been advised to rest by doctors, addressed the conference by video message.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Bill Gates called for a "green industrial revolution" to beat the climate crisis.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fossil fuel industry was the largest delegation at the conference, with 503 people accredited.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In October 2021, China's leader Xi Jinping announced he would not be attending the conference in person and instead delivered a written address as the organizers did not provide an opportunity for a video address.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] With greenhouse gas emissions by China being the world's largest, Reuters said this made it less likely the conference would result in a significant climate deal.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, a Chinese delegation led by climate change envoy Xie Zhenhua did attend.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The 2021 global energy crisis intensified pressures on China ahead of the summit.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The prime ministers or heads of state of South Africa, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Mexico, Brazil, Turkey, Malaysia and Vatican City also did not attend the meeting.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russian president Vladimir Putin said his non-attendance was due to concerns relating to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Iranian president Ebrahim Raisi did not attend; a formal request had been made by Struan Stevenson and Iranian exiles of the National Council of Resistance of Iran to the Scotland police, to arrest Raisi for crimes against humanity if he attended based on the legal concept of universal jurisdiction.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Saudi crown prince Mohammed bin Salman also did not attend the summit.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Brazilian president Jair Bolsonaro, who faced international condemnation over rising deforestation of the Amazon rainforest, also decided not to attend the summit personally.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The non-attendance of both Putin and Xi received criticism from U.S. president Joe Biden and former American president Barack Obama.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Myanmar and Afghanistan were entirely absent; both countries had their UN-recognized governments ousted militarily in 2021.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Myanmar military junta was blocked from entry to the summit.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Six exiled Afghan climate experts had their applications rejected by the UNFCCC.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Additionally, the island nation of Kiribati did not send participants, while fellow island nations Vanuatu and Samoa registered but did not send a delegation.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Under the Paris Agreement, countries submitted pledges called nationally determined contributions, to limit their greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Under the framework of the Paris Agreement, each country is expected to submit enhanced nationally determined contributions every five years, to ratchet up the ambition to mitigate climate change.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] When the Paris Agreement was signed at COP21, the conference of 2020 was set to be the first ratcheting up.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Even though the 2020 conference was postponed to 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, dozens of countries still had not updated their pledges by early October 2021.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Collective progress towards implementation of the Paris Agreement in mitigation, adaptation and finance flows and means of implementation and support will be measured by global stocktakes, the first of which is due to be completed in 2023.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 November 2021, the participating 197 countries agreed to a new deal, known as the Glasgow Climate Pact, aimed at staving off dangerous climate change.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The final agreement explicitly mentions coal, which is the single biggest contributor to climate change.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previous COP agreements have not mentioned coal, oil or gas, or even fossil fuels in general, as a driver, or major cause of climate change, making the Glasgow Climate Pact the first ever climate deal to explicitly plan to reduce unabated coal power.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The wording in the agreement refers to an intention to "phase down" use of unabated coal power, rather than to phase it out.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] From this wording it implicitly follows that utilizing coal power with "abation" (net-zero emission), e.g. by neutralizing the resulting carbon dioxide via the CO2-to-stone process, need not be reduced.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, this carbon capture and storage is too expensive for most coal fired power stations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Over 140 countries pledged to reach net-zero emissions.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 100 countries, including Brazil, pledged to reverse deforestation by 2030.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The final text of the Glasgow Climate Pact include a call to: "accelerating efforts towards... phase-out of inefficient fossil fuel subsidies".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 40 countries pledged to move away from coal.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United States and China reached an agreement about cooperation on measures to stop climate change, including lowering methane emissions, phasing out the use of coal, and forest conservation.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] 39 countries and institutions signed the Glasgow Statement, an international agreement to shift international public finance away from fossil fuels towards clean energy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] If implemented properly, the Glasgow Statement will shift $28 billion per year from fossil fuels to clean energy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India promised to draw half of its energy requirement from renewable sources by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2070.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers such as GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover, and Mercedes-Benz have committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Major car manufacturing nations like China, the US, Japan, Germany, and South Korea, as well as Toyota, Volkswagen, Nissan-Renault-Mitsubishi, Stellantis, Honda, and Hyundai had not signed up to the pledge.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] New pledges for financial help for climate change mitigation and adaptation were announced.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Climate Action Tracker on 9 November 2021, described the results as follows: the global temperature will rise by 2.7 °C by the end of the century with current policies.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if only the pledges for 2030 are implemented, by 2.1 °C if the long-term targets are also achieved and by 1.8 °C if all the announced targets are fully achieved.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Glasgow Financial Alliance for Net Zero (GFANZ) announced that financial institutions controlling $130 trillion were now signed up to 'net zero' emissions pledges by 2050.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The world leaders' summit was on 1 and 2 November, with each leader giving a national statement.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An important goal of the conference organizers is to keep a 1.5 °C (2.7 °F) temperature rise within reach.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the BBC, negotiators who may be key to the dealmaking include Xie Zhenhua, Ayman Shasly, Sheikh Hasina and Teresa Ribera.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China said it aims to peak CO2 emissions before 2030 and to become carbon neutral by 2060.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It was asked to set a clear earlier date as this would have a very large "positive impact" on the Paris Agreement targets.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Officials later said the 2030 target was something to "strive to" and not something to be ensured.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Signatories of the 2014 agreement, the New York Declaration on Forests, pledged to half deforestation by 2020 and end it by 2030; however, in the 2014–2020 period deforestation increased.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Indonesia's environment minister Siti Nurbaya Bakar stated that "forcing Indonesia to zero deforestation in 2030 is clearly inappropriate and unfair".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Article 6 of the Paris Agreement, which describes rules for an international carbon market (such as for trees in the deforestation agreement) and other forms of international cooperation, is being discussed as it is the last piece of the rulebook remaining to be finalized.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Although the parties have agreed in principle to avoid double counting of emission reduction across more than one country's greenhouse gas inventory, exactly how much double counting will actually occur remains unclear.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Carrying forward pre-2020 Kyoto carbon credits will be discussed, but is highly unlikely to be agreed.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Therefore, Article 6 rules could make a big difference to future emissions.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Climate finance for adaptation and mitigation was one of the principal topics of negotiation.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Poor countries want more money for adaptation, whereas donors prefer to finance mitigation as that has a chance of making a profit.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Appointed to the role of Climate Finance Adviser was Mark Carney, former Governor of the Bank of England.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Paris agreement included US$100 billion annually in finance by 2020 for developing countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, wealthy countries failed to live up to that promise, with members of the OECD behind in their commitments and unlikely to reach the agreed amount before 2023.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A group of large finance companies committed to net zero portfolios and loan books by 2050.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Scotland became the first country to contribute to a loss and damage fund.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] South Africa is set to receive $8.5 billion to end its reliance on coal, details are sparse regarding capping mines, exports and local community support for the workers in the industry.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Countries including Chile, Poland, Ukraine, South Korea, Indonesia and Vietnam also agreed to phase out coal in the 2030s for major economies, and the 2040s for poorer nations.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] These nations include some of the world's most intensive users of coal.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, they do not include the world's largest users of the fuel, China, India, and the United States of America.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Japan is to invest $100 million in the transformation of fossil-fired plants into ones based on ammonia and hydrogen fuel.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The US and many other countries agreed to limit methane emissions.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 80 countries signed up to a global methane pledge, agreeing to cut emissions by 30% by the end of the decade.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The US and European leaders say tackling the potent greenhouse gas is crucial to keeping warming limited to 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Australia, China, Russia, India and Iran did not sign the deal, but it is hoped more countries will join later.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia demanded sanction relief on green investment projects for energy companies such as Gazprom.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia's climate envoy Ruslan Edelgeriyev accused Western countries of hypocrisy for urging Russia "to reduce methane leakages and yet we have Gazprom under sanctions".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Many attendees committed to net-zero carbon emissions, with India and Japan making specific commitments at the conference.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India, the third-largest emitter of carbon dioxide by jurisdiction, set the latest target date planning to be net-zero by 2070.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Japan is to offer up to $10 billion in additional funding to support decarbonization in Asia.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Earlier in October, China—the largest emitter of carbon dioxide by jurisdiction—had committed to net-zero carbon emissions by 2060, and it was believed by the British government that India would issue a similar commitment.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] However, this was the first time that a date for carbon neutrality had been given as part of India's climate policy.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Green hydrogen has emerged as one of the major areas where companies can collaborate to help decarbonize hard to abate industries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Big city mayors concerned about climate—the C40 Cities Climate Leadership Group—such as Istanbul Mayor Ekrem İmamoğlu, called for more urban climate adaptation, especially in low-income countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] 45 countries, including the UK, U.S., Japan, Germany, India, Indonesia, Morocco, Vietnam, Philippines, Gabon, Ethiopia, Ghana and Uruguay, pledged to give more than $4 billion for transition to sustainable agriculture.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A draft text published on 10 November asked governments to accelerate phase-outs and desubsidization of fossil fuels, the largest source of (anthropogenic) global greenhouse gas emissions, but was opposed by several countries with large fossil fuels based economic sectors.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Business leaders and politicians including Jeff Bezos, Prince Charles, Boris Johnson, Joe Biden and Angela Merkel who travelled to Glasgow in private airplanes were accused of hypocrisy by commentators and campaigners.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Event planners, however, insisted that the conference would be carbon-neutral.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Around 400 private jets arrived at Glasgow for the talks.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In October 2021, the BBC reported that a huge leak of documents revealed that Saudi Arabia, Japan and Australia were among countries asking the UN to play down the need to move rapidly away from fossil fuels.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It also showed that some wealthy nations (including Switzerland and Australia) were questioning paying more to poorer states to move to greener technologies.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The BBC reported that the lobbying raised questions for the COP26 climate summit.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Australian government has been criticized for hosting a fossil fuel company at the summit, not enhancing its ambitions closer to its capacities, not pledging to reduce methane emissions and not pledging to phase out coal.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In an interview shortly before the conference, Greta Thunberg, asked how optimistic she was that the conference could achieve anything, responded "Nothing has changed from previous years really.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The leaders will say 'we'll do this and we'll do this, and we will put our forces together and achieve this', and then they will do nothing.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Maybe some symbolic things and creative accounting and things that don't really have a big impact.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] By 1 November, at the outset of the conference, the climate change activist Greta Thunberg criticized the summit at a protest in Glasgow with members from the organization Fridays for Future, saying "This COP26 is so far just like the previous COPs and that has led us nowhere.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 5 November, a Fridays for Future protest at which Thunberg spoke gathered thousands of people, largely schoolchildren.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Attendees supported more immediate and far-reaching action on climate change.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Glasgow City Council and most neighbouring councils stated that students would not be punished if parents informed their schools of the absence.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 6 November—the Global Day of Action for Climate Justice—around 100,000 people joined a march in Glasgow, according to BBC News, with coaches and group cycle rides organized for participants to travel from around the United Kingdom.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The protests were the largest in Glasgow since anti-Iraq War marches in 2003.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A London march drew 10,000 people according to police and 20,000 according to organizers.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] *The Times* anticipated that total participants would number over two million.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An additional 100 marches took place elsewhere in the country, with a total of 300 protests across 100 countries, according to *The Guardian*.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 8 November, Fridays for Future activists including Dominika Lasota and Nicole Becker held a protest prior to a speech by former US president Barack Obama, arguing that he had failed to fulfill his promise to provide US$100 billion in climate funding to developing countries.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The protestors held banners stating, "Show us the money".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Vanessa Nakate and indigenous activists gave speeches at Glasgow.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Issues highlighted by protesters included putting corporate interests at the forefront and politicians' failure to address the climate emergency with the required urgency as well as its underlying causes.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kahnawake Mohawk people, ecology scientists, vegan activists, trade unionists and socialists were present at marches.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] One intended participant, the Israeli energy minister Karine Elharrar, was unable to attend on 1 November due to wheelchair accessibility issues.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The sustainability of the COP26 menu was criticized by the animal and climate justice group Animal Rebellion, with almost 60% of the menu being meat and dairy based, and dishes labelled as high-carbon being served at food stands.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The head of catering at COP26, Lorna Wilson, said that staff had been "working towards" a catering strategy of 95% food from the UK and 5% from abroad.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Wilson said the menu was 40% plant-based and 60% vegetarian overall.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The event eliminated single-use cups and plastics.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There was concern about the inclusion and influence of large delegations of industries, particularly big polluting companies, and financial organizations involved in the causes of greenhouse gas emissions at the conference.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Further criticisms of the results include that it needs not only commitments but also clear directions for mitigation and adaptation and robust mechanisms put in place for the relevant parties to be held accountable to their commitments.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to critics, such issues could turn the conference into a "greenwashing" event of empty promises.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There is a criticism about the lack of people from most affected people and areas.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kaossara Sani became one of the persons who came from this place and sent her criticism by sending her manifesto to Forbes about what happened in Sahel and her criticism to COP26.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Academicians and practitioners on the field have floated several missing links of COP26 particularly the approach to climate change, disasters and public health consequences stemming from the meeting and how the neglect of healthcare will impact the Asia Pacific Region as a whole.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the Institute for Strategic Dialogue and a network of journalism organizations, the COP meeting became a target for climate misinformation, prominently "narratives of delay".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 9 November, Climate Action Tracker reported that the global human civilization is on track for a 2.7 °C temperature increase in the Earth system by the end of the century with current policies.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if the pledges for 2030 will be implemented, by 2.1 °C if the long-term targets will be implemented also and by 1.8 °C if in addition all the targets in discussion will be fully implemented.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Current targets for 2030 remain "totally inadequate".
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Coal and natural gas consumption are the main cause for the gap between pledges and policies.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 10 November, it was reported that the United States and China agreed on a framework to reduce carbon emissions by cooperating on measures to lower the use of methane, phase out the use of coal and increased protection of forests.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The request was criticized as illogical and self-defeating as it would end up harming people in developing countries the most and an article in the *Daily Beast* described the request as an attempt by China to sabotage the draft commitment.
[src:2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference/2021-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China was responsible for around 27% of the world's current GHG emissions in 2019.
